![](https://github.com/rstudio/hex-stickers/raw/main/thumbs/purrr.png){fig-align='center' width=60%} ::: ::: ::: ## Goals for Today - **Review** core principles of: - `dyplr` (data manipulation) - `tidyr` (data transformation and reshaping) ::::: {.columns style="display: flex !important; height: 90%;"} ::: {.column width="70%" style="display: flex; align-items: center;"} # Data Manipulation in `dplyr` ::: ::: {.column width="30%" style="display: flex; justify-content: center; align-items: center;"} ::: {.cell layout-align="center"} ::: {.cell-output-display} ![](https://github.com/rstudio/hex-stickers/raw/main/thumbs/dplyr.png){fig-align='center'} ::: ::: ::: ::::: # `dplyr` Core Functions 1. **`%>%`**: The pipe. Read as "and then." 2. **`filter()`**: Pick observations (rows) by their values. 3. **`select()`**: Pick variables (columns) by their names. 4. **`arrange()`**: Reorder the rows. 5. **`group_by()`**: Implicitly split the data set by grouping by names (columns). 6. **`mutate()`**: Create new variables with functions of existing variables. 7. **`summarize()` / `summarise()`**: Collapse many values down to a single summary. ## Core Functions :::::: columns :::: {.column width="40%"} ::: nonincremental 1. **`%>%`** 2. **`filter()`** 3. **`select()`** 4. **`arrange()`** 5. **`group_by()`** 6. **`mutate()`** 7. **`summarize()`** ::: :::: ::: {.column width="60%" style="text-align: center; background-color: #FFD966; color: black; border: 5px solid #033266;"} Although each of these functions are powerful alone, they are incredibly powerful in conjunction with one another. So below, I'll briefly introduce each function, then link them all together using an example of basic data cleaning and summary. ::: :::::: ## 1. `%>%` - The pipe `%>%` is wonderful. It makes coding intuitive. Often in coding, you need to use so-called nested functions. For example, you might want to round a number after taking the square of 43. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} sqrt(43) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` [1] 6.557439 ``` ::: ```{.r .cell-code} round(sqrt(43), 2) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` [1] 6.56 ``` ::: ::: The issue with this comes whenever we need to do a series of operations on a data set or other type of object. In such cases, if we run it in a single call, then we have to start in the middle and read our way out. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} round(sqrt(43/2), 2) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` [1] 4.64 ``` ::: ::: The pipe solves this by allowing you to read from left to right (or top to bottom). The easiest way to think of it is that each call of `%>%` reads and operates as "and then." So with the rounded square root of 43, for example: ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} sqrt(43) %>% round(2) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` [1] 6.56 ``` ::: ::: ## 2. `filter()` Often times, when conducting research (experiments or otherwise), there are observations (people, specific trials, etc.) that you don't want to include. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} data(bfi) # grab the bfi data from the psych package bfi <- bfi %>% as_tibble() head(bfi) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} `````{=html}
````` ::: ::: Often times, when conducting research (experiments or otherwise), there are observations (people, specific trials, etc.) that you don't want to include. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} summary(bfi$age) # get age descriptives ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` Min. 1st Qu. Median Mean 3rd Qu. Max. 3.00 20.00 26.00 28.78 35.00 86.00 ``` ::: ::: Often times, when conducting research (experiments or otherwise), there are observations (people, specific trials, etc.) that you don't want to include. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code code-line-numbers="|2"} bfi2 <- bfi %>% # see a pipe! filter(age <= 18) # filter to age up to 18 summary(bfi2$age) # summary of the new data ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` Min. 1st Qu. Median Mean 3rd Qu. Max. 3.0 16.0 17.0 16.3 18.0 18.0 ``` ::: ::: But this isn't quite right. We still have folks below 12. But, the beauty of `filter()` is that you can do sequence of `OR` and `AND` statements when there is more than one condition, such as up to 18 `AND` at least 12. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} bfi2 <- bfi %>% filter(age <= 18 & age >= 12) # filter to age up to 18 and at least 12 summary(bfi2$age) # summary of the new data ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` Min. 1st Qu. Median Mean 3rd Qu. Max. 12.0 16.0 17.0 16.4 18.0 18.0 ``` ::: ::: Got it! - But filter works for more use cases than just conditional - `<`, `>`, `<=`, and `>=` - It can also be used for cases where we want a single values to match cases with text. - To do that, let's convert one of the variables in the `bfi` data frame to a string. - So let's change gender (1 = male, 2 = female) to text (we'll get into factors later). ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} bfi$education <- plyr::mapvalues(bfi$education, 1:5, c("Below HS", "HS", "Some College", "College", "Higher Degree")) ``` ::: Now let's try a few things: **1. Create a data set with only individuals with some college (`==`).** ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} bfi2 <- bfi %>% filter(education == "Some College") unique(bfi2$education) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` [1] "Some College" ``` ::: ::: **2. Create a data set with only people age 18 (`==`).** ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} bfi2 <- bfi %>% filter(age == 18) summary(bfi2$age) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` Min. 1st Qu. Median Mean 3rd Qu. Max. 18 18 18 18 18 18 ``` ::: ::: **3. Create a data set with individuals with some college or above (`%in%`).** ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} bfi2 <- bfi %>% filter(education %in% c("Some College", "College", "Higher Degree")) unique(bfi2$education) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` [1] "Some College" "Higher Degree" "College" ``` ::: ::: `%in%` is great. It compares a column to a vector rather than just a single value, you can compare it to several ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} bfi2 <- bfi %>% filter(age %in% 12:18) summary(bfi2$age) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` Min. 1st Qu. Median Mean 3rd Qu. Max. 12.0 16.0 17.0 16.4 18.0 18.0 ``` ::: ::: ## 3. `select()` - If `filter()` is for pulling certain observations (rows), then `select()` is for pulling certain variables (columns). - it's good practice to remove these columns to stop your environment from becoming cluttered and eating up your RAM. - In our `bfi` data, most of these have been pre-removed, so instead, we'll imagine we don't want to use any indicators of Agreeableness (A1-A5) and that we aren't interested in gender. - With `select()`, there are few ways choose variables. We can bare quote name the ones we want to keep, bare quote names we want to remove, or use any of a number of `select()` helper functions. ### A. Bare quote columns we want to keep: ::::: columns ::: column ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code code-line-numbers="|2"} bfi %>% select(C1, C2, C3, C4, C5) %>% print(n = 6) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 2,800 × 5 C1 C2 C3 C4 C5 1 2 3 3 4 4 2 5 4 4 3 4 3 4 5 4 2 5 4 4 4 3 5 5 5 4 4 5 3 2 6 6 6 6 1 3 # ℹ 2,794 more rows ``` ::: ::: ::: ::: column ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code code-line-numbers="|2"} bfi %>% select(C1:C5) %>% print(n = 6) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 2,800 × 5 C1 C2 C3 C4 C5 1 2 3 3 4 4 2 5 4 4 3 4 3 4 5 4 2 5 4 4 4 3 5 5 5 4 4 5 3 2 6 6 6 6 1 3 # ℹ 2,794 more rows ``` ::: ::: ::: ::::: ### B. Bare quote columns we don't want to keep: ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code code-line-numbers="|2"} bfi %>% select(-(A1:A5), -gender) %>% # Note the `()` around the columns print(n = 6) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 2,800 × 22 C1 C2 C3 C4 C5 E1 E2 E3 E4 E5 N1 N2 N3 1 2 3 3 4 4 3 3 3 4 4 3 4 2 2 5 4 4 3 4 1 1 6 4 3 3 3 3 3 4 5 4 2 5 2 4 4 4 5 4 5 4 4 4 4 3 5 5 5 3 4 4 4 2 5 2 5 4 4 5 3 2 2 2 5 4 5 2 3 4 6 6 6 6 1 3 2 1 6 5 6 3 5 2 # ℹ 2,794 more rows # ℹ 9 more variables: N4 , N5 , O1 , O2 , O3 , # O4 , O5 , education , age ``` ::: ::: ### C. Add or remove using `select()` helper functions. :::::: columns ::: {.column width="40%"} - `starts_with()`\ - `ends_with()` - `contains()` - `matches()` - `num_range()` - `one_of()` - `all_of()` ::: :::: {.column width="60%"} ::: fragment ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} bfi %>% select(starts_with("C")) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} `````{=html}
````` ::: ::: ::: :::: :::::: ## 4. `arrange()` - Sometimes, either in order to get a better sense of our data or in order to well, order our data, we want to sort it - Although there is a base `R` `sort()` function, the `arrange()` function is `tidyverse` version that plays nicely with other `tidyverse functions`. ::::: columns So in our previous examples, we could also `arrange()` our data by age or education, rather than simply filtering. (Or as we'll see later, we can do both!) ::: {.column width="50%"} ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code code-line-numbers="|4"} # sort by age bfi %>% select(gender:age) %>% arrange(age) %>% print(n = 6) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 2,800 × 3 gender education age 1 1 Higher Degree 3 2 2 9 3 2 Some College 11 4 2 11 5 2 11 6 2 12 # ℹ 2,794 more rows ``` ::: ::: ::: ::: {.column width="50%"} ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code code-line-numbers="|4"} # sort by education bfi %>% select(gender:age) %>% arrange(education) %>% print(n = 6) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 2,800 × 3 gender education age 1 1 Below HS 19 2 1 Below HS 21 3 1 Below HS 17 4 1 Below HS 18 5 1 Below HS 18 6 2 Below HS 18 # ℹ 2,794 more rows ``` ::: ::: ::: ::::: We can also arrange by multiple columns, like if we wanted to sort by gender then education: ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} bfi %>% select(gender:age) %>% arrange(gender, education) %>% print(n = 6) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 2,800 × 3 gender education age 1 1 Below HS 19 2 1 Below HS 21 3 1 Below HS 17 4 1 Below HS 18 5 1 Below HS 18 6 1 Below HS 32 # ℹ 2,794 more rows ``` ::: ::: # Bringing it all together: Split-Apply-Combine - Much of the power of `dplyr` functions lay in the split-apply-combine method - A given set of of data are: - *split* into smaller chunks - then a function or series of functions are *applied* to each chunk - and then the chunks are *combined* back together ## 5. `group_by()` - The `group_by()` function is the "split" of the method - It basically implicitly breaks the data set into chunks by whatever bare quoted column(s)/variable(s) are supplied as arguments. So imagine that we wanted to `group_by()` education levels to get average ages at each level ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} bfi %>% select(starts_with("C"), age, gender, education) %>% group_by(education) %>% print(n = 6) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 2,800 × 8 # Groups: education [6] C1 C2 C3 C4 C5 age gender education 1 2 3 3 4 4 16 1 2 5 4 4 3 4 18 2 3 4 5 4 2 5 17 2 4 4 4 3 5 5 17 2 5 4 4 5 3 2 17 1 6 6 6 6 1 3 21 2 Some College # ℹ 2,794 more rows ``` ::: ::: - Hadley's first law of data cleaning: "What is split, must be combined" - This is super easy with the `ungroup()` function: ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} bfi %>% select(starts_with("C"), age, gender, education) %>% group_by(education) %>% ungroup() %>% print(n = 6) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 2,800 × 8 C1 C2 C3 C4 C5 age gender education 1 2 3 3 4 4 16 1 2 5 4 4 3 4 18 2 3 4 5 4 2 5 17 2 4 4 4 3 5 5 17 2 5 4 4 5 3 2 17 1 6 6 6 6 1 3 21 2 Some College # ℹ 2,794 more rows ``` ::: ::: Multiple `group_by()` calls overwrites previous calls: ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} bfi %>% select(starts_with("C"), age, gender, education) %>% group_by(education) %>% group_by(gender, age) %>% print(n = 6) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 2,800 × 8 # Groups: gender, age [115] C1 C2 C3 C4 C5 age gender education 1 2 3 3 4 4 16 1 2 5 4 4 3 4 18 2 3 4 5 4 2 5 17 2 4 4 4 3 5 5 17 2 5 4 4 5 3 2 17 1 6 6 6 6 1 3 21 2 Some College # ℹ 2,794 more rows ``` ::: ::: ## 6. `mutate()` - `mutate()` is one of your "apply" functions - When you use `mutate()`, the resulting data frame will have the same number of rows you started with - You are directly mutating the existing data frame, either modifying existing columns or creating new ones To demonstrate, let's add a column that indicated average age levels within each age group ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} bfi %>% select(starts_with("C"), age, gender, education) %>% arrange(education) %>% group_by(education) %>% mutate(age_by_edu = mean(age, na.rm = T)) %>% print(n = 6) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 2,800 × 9 # Groups: education [6] C1 C2 C3 C4 C5 age gender education age_by_edu 1 6 6 3 4 5 19 1 Below HS 25.1 2 4 3 5 3 2 21 1 Below HS 25.1 3 5 5 5 2 2 17 1 Below HS 25.1 4 5 5 4 1 1 18 1 Below HS 25.1 5 4 5 4 3 3 18 1 Below HS 25.1 6 3 2 3 4 6 18 2 Below HS 25.1 # ℹ 2,794 more rows ``` ::: ::: `mutate()` is also super useful even when you aren't grouping We can create a new category ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} bfi %>% select(starts_with("C"), age, gender, education) %>% mutate(gender_cat = plyr::mapvalues(gender, c(1,2), c("Male", "Female"))) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} `````{=html}
````` ::: ::: We could also just overwrite it: ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} bfi %>% select(starts_with("C"), age, gender, education) %>% mutate(gender = plyr::mapvalues(gender, c(1,2), c("Male", "Female"))) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} `````{=html}
````` ::: ::: ## 7. `summarize()` / `summarise()` - `summarize()` is one of your "apply" functions - The resulting data frame will have the same number of rows as your grouping variable - You number of groups is 1 for ungrouped data frames ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} # group_by() education bfi %>% select(starts_with("C"), age, gender, education) %>% arrange(education) %>% group_by(education) %>% summarize(age_by_edu = mean(age, na.rm = T)) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} `````{=html}
````` ::: ::: ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} # no groups bfi %>% select(starts_with("C"), age, gender, education) %>% arrange(education) %>% summarize(age_by_edu = mean(age, na.rm = T)) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} `````{=html}
````` ::: ::: ::::: {.columns .v-center-container} ::: {.column width="70%"}

Data Wrangling in `tidyr`

::: ::: {.column width="30%"} ::: {.cell layout-align="center"} ```{.r .cell-code} knitr::include_graphics("https://github.com/rstudio/hex-stickers/raw/master/thumbs/tidyr.png") ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} ![](https://github.com/rstudio/hex-stickers/raw/master/thumbs/tidyr.png){fig-align='center'} ::: ::: ::: ::::: # `tidyr` - Now, let's build off what we learned from dplyr and focus on *reshaping* and *merging* our data. - First, the reshapers: 1. `pivot_longer()`, which takes a "wide" format data frame and makes it long.\ 2. `pivot_wider()`, which takes a "long" format data frame and makes it wide. - Next, the mergers: 3. `full_join()`, which merges *all* rows in either data frame\ 4. `inner_join()`, which merges rows whose keys are present in *both* data frames\ 5. `left_join()`, which "prioritizes" the first data set\ 6. `right_join()`, which "prioritizes" the second data set (See also:`anti_join()` and `semi_join()`) # Key `tidyr` Functions ## 1. `pivot_longer()` - (Formerly `gather()`) Makes wide data long, based on a key - Core arguments: - `data`: the data, blank if piped - `cols`: columns to be made long, selected via `select()` calls - `names_to`: name(s) of key column(s) in new long data frame (string or string vector) - `values_to`: name of values in new long data frame (string) - `names_sep`: separator in column headers, if multiple keys - `values_drop_na`: drop missing cells (similar to `na.rm = T`) ### Basic Application Let's start with an easy one -- one key, one value: ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} bfi %>% rownames_to_column("SID") %>% pivot_longer( cols = A1:O5 , names_to = "item" , values_to = "values" , values_drop_na = T ) %>% print(n = 8) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 69,492 × 6 SID gender education age item values 1 1 1 16 A1 2 2 1 1 16 A2 4 3 1 1 16 A3 3 4 1 1 16 A4 4 5 1 1 16 A5 4 6 1 1 16 C1 2 7 1 1 16 C2 3 8 1 1 16 C3 3 # ℹ 69,484 more rows ``` ::: ::: ### More Advanced Application Now a harder one -- two keys, one value: ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} bfi %>% rownames_to_column("SID") %>% pivot_longer( cols = A1:O5 , names_to = c("trait", "item_num") , names_sep = -1 , values_to = "values" , values_drop_na = T ) %>% print(n = 8) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 69,492 × 7 SID gender education age trait item_num values 1 1 1 16 A 1 2 2 1 1 16 A 2 4 3 1 1 16 A 3 3 4 1 1 16 A 4 4 5 1 1 16 A 5 4 6 1 1 16 C 1 2 7 1 1 16 C 2 3 8 1 1 16 C 3 3 # ℹ 69,484 more rows ``` ::: ::: ## 2. `pivot_wider()` {.smaller} - (Formerly `spread()`) Makes wide data long, based on a key - Core arguments: - `data`: the data, blank if piped - `names_from`: name(s) of key column(s) in new long data frame (string or string vector) - `names_sep`: separator in column headers, if multiple keys - `names_glue`: specify multiple or custom separators of multiple keys - `values_from`: name of values in new long data frame (string) - `values_fn`: function applied to data with duplicate labels ### Basic Application ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} bfi_long <- bfi %>% rownames_to_column("SID") %>% pivot_longer( cols = A1:O5 , names_to = "item" , values_to = "values" , values_drop_na = T ) ``` ::: ### More Advanced ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} bfi_long <- bfi %>% rownames_to_column("SID") %>% pivot_longer( cols = A1:O5 , names_to = c("trait", "item_num") , names_sep = -1 , values_to = "values" , values_drop_na = T ) ``` ::: ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} bfi_long %>% pivot_wider( names_from = c("trait", "item_num") , values_from = "values" , names_sep = "_" ) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} `````{=html}
````` ::: ::: ### A Little More Advanced ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} bfi_long %>% select(-item_num) %>% pivot_wider( names_from = "trait" , values_from = "values" , names_sep = "_" , values_fn = mean ) ``` ::: {.cell-output-display} `````{=html}
````` ::: ::: # More `dplyr` Functions ## The `_join()` Functions - Often we may need to pull different data from different sources - There are lots of reasons to need to do this - We don't have time to get into all the use cases here, so we'll talk about them in high level terms - We'll focus on: - `full_join()` - `inner_join()` - `left_join()` - `right_join()` - Let's separate demographic and BFI data ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code code-line-numbers="|3"} bfi_only <- bfi %>% rownames_to_column("SID") %>% select(SID, matches("[0-9]")) bfi_only %>% as_tibble() %>% print(n = 6) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 2,800 × 26 SID A1 A2 A3 A4 A5 C1 C2 C3 C4 C5 E1 E2 1 1 2 4 3 4 4 2 3 3 4 4 3 3 2 2 2 4 5 2 5 5 4 4 3 4 1 1 3 3 5 4 5 4 4 4 5 4 2 5 2 4 4 4 4 4 6 5 5 4 4 3 5 5 5 3 5 5 2 3 3 4 5 4 4 5 3 2 2 2 6 6 6 6 5 6 5 6 6 6 1 3 2 1 # ℹ 2,794 more rows # ℹ 13 more variables: E3 , E4 , E5 , N1 , N2 , # N3 , N4 , N5 , O1 , O2 , O3 , O4 , # O5 ``` ::: ::: ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code code-line-numbers="|3"} bfi_dem <- bfi %>% rownames_to_column("SID") %>% select(SID, education, gender, age) bfi_dem %>% as_tibble() %>% print(n = 6) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 2,800 × 4 SID education gender age 1 1 1 16 2 2 2 18 3 3 2 17 4 4 2 17 5 5 1 17 6 6 Some College 2 21 # ℹ 2,794 more rows ``` ::: ::: Before we get into it, as a reminder, this is what the data set looks like before we do any joining: ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} bfi %>% rownames_to_column("SID") %>% as_tibble() %>% print(n = 6) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 2,800 × 29 SID A1 A2 A3 A4 A5 C1 C2 C3 C4 C5 E1 E2 1 1 2 4 3 4 4 2 3 3 4 4 3 3 2 2 2 4 5 2 5 5 4 4 3 4 1 1 3 3 5 4 5 4 4 4 5 4 2 5 2 4 4 4 4 4 6 5 5 4 4 3 5 5 5 3 5 5 2 3 3 4 5 4 4 5 3 2 2 2 6 6 6 6 5 6 5 6 6 6 1 3 2 1 # ℹ 2,794 more rows # ℹ 16 more variables: E3 , E4 , E5 , N1 , N2 , # N3 , N4 , N5 , O1 , O2 , O3 , O4 , # O5 , gender , education , age ``` ::: ::: ## 3. `full_join()` Most simply, we can put those back together keeping all observations. ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code} bfi_only %>% full_join(bfi_dem) %>% as_tibble() %>% print(n = 6) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` Joining with `by = join_by(SID)` ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 2,800 × 29 SID A1 A2 A3 A4 A5 C1 C2 C3 C4 C5 E1 E2 1 1 2 4 3 4 4 2 3 3 4 4 3 3 2 2 2 4 5 2 5 5 4 4 3 4 1 1 3 3 5 4 5 4 4 4 5 4 2 5 2 4 4 4 4 4 6 5 5 4 4 3 5 5 5 3 5 5 2 3 3 4 5 4 4 5 3 2 2 2 6 6 6 6 5 6 5 6 6 6 1 3 2 1 # ℹ 2,794 more rows # ℹ 16 more variables: E3 , E4 , E5 , N1 , N2 , # N3 , N4 , N5 , O1 , O2 , O3 , O4 , # O5 , education , gender , age ``` ::: ::: ## 4. `inner_join()` We can also keep all rows present in *both* data frames ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code code-line-numbers="|1-2|4-5|3"} bfi_dem %>% filter(row_number() %in% 1:1700) %>% inner_join( bfi_only %>% filter(row_number() %in% 1200:2800) ) %>% as_tibble() %>% print(n = 6) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` Joining with `by = join_by(SID)` ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 501 × 29 SID education gender age A1 A2 A3 A4 A5 C1 C2 C3 1 1200 Some Colle… 2 18 1 5 6 5 5 5 6 5 2 1201 College 2 29 1 5 6 5 5 2 1 4 3 1202 Higher Deg… 1 46 2 5 6 5 6 6 6 6 4 1203 Higher Deg… 1 58 5 4 4 4 5 4 4 5 5 1204 Higher Deg… 2 38 1 4 6 6 6 4 4 5 6 1205 Higher Deg… 2 27 2 3 1 1 1 4 2 2 # ℹ 495 more rows # ℹ 17 more variables: C4 , C5 , E1 , E2 , E3 , # E4 , E5 , N1 , N2 , N3 , N4 , N5 , # O1 , O2 , O3 , O4 , O5 ``` ::: ::: ## 5. `left_join()` Or all rows present in the left (first) data frame, perhaps if it's a subset of people with complete data ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code code-line-numbers="|2|3"} bfi_dem %>% drop_na() %>% left_join(bfi_only) %>% as_tibble() %>% print(n = 6) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` Joining with `by = join_by(SID)` ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 2,577 × 29 SID education gender age A1 A2 A3 A4 A5 C1 C2 C3 1 6 Some Colle… 2 21 6 6 5 6 5 6 6 6 2 8 HS 1 19 4 3 1 5 1 3 2 4 3 9 Below HS 1 19 4 3 6 3 3 6 6 3 4 11 Below HS 1 21 4 4 5 6 5 4 3 5 5 15 Below HS 1 17 4 5 2 2 1 5 5 5 6 23 Higher Deg… 1 68 1 5 6 5 6 4 3 2 # ℹ 2,571 more rows # ℹ 17 more variables: C4 , C5 , E1 , E2 , E3 , # E4 , E5 , N1 , N2 , N3 , N4 , N5 , # O1 , O2 , O3 , O4 , O5 ``` ::: ::: ## 6. `right_join()` Or all rows present in the right (second) data frame, such as I do when I join a codebook with raw data ::: {.cell} ```{.r .cell-code code-line-numbers="|3"} bfi_dem %>% drop_na() %>% right_join(bfi_only) %>% as_tibble() %>% print(n = 6) ``` ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stderr} ``` Joining with `by = join_by(SID)` ``` ::: ::: {.cell-output .cell-output-stdout} ``` # A tibble: 2,800 × 29 SID education gender age A1 A2 A3 A4 A5 C1 C2 C3 1 6 Some Colle… 2 21 6 6 5 6 5 6 6 6 2 8 HS 1 19 4 3 1 5 1 3 2 4 3 9 Below HS 1 19 4 3 6 3 3 6 6 3 4 11 Below HS 1 21 4 4 5 6 5 4 3 5 5 15 Below HS 1 17 4 5 2 2 1 5 5 5 6 23 Higher Deg… 1 68 1 5 6 5 6 4 3 2 # ℹ 2,794 more rows # ℹ 17 more variables: C4 , C5 , E1 , E2 , E3 , # E4 , E5 , N1 , N2 , N3 , N4 , N5 , # O1 , O2 , O3 , O4 , O5 ``` ::: :::
